<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-5715-2439> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Drummer, by Terecita Romero (Cochiti Pueblo); ca. 1965\r\nPottery, pigments; h. 16,4 cm.\r\nRMV 5715-2439; Elisabeth Houtzager collection\r\nThis drummer figure represents a transitional period between large single standing figurines of the late nineteenth and early twentieth century and the seated and often sentimental seated storytellers of the last decades of the twentieth century. Romero’s drummer is considerably smaller than the early standing figures. In addition, unlike the late twentieth century seated storytellers there is not a multitude of children sitting on the legs and arms of the drummer (cf. Babcock et.al. 1986).\r\n\r\nThroughout the last 150 years, Cochiti potters used figurines to engage in social criticism conducting discourse on the changing circumstances and occupants of the southwest. The early figures most often depict non-Cochiti people and often use parody. While we cannot know individual potters intentions, we can infer that the making of figurines was a means of coping with foreigners a well as a form of social empowerment. In contrast this figure is nativistic in its intentions and style, reinforcing deep cultural values and simultaneously teaching outsiders (for whom these figures were made to sell to) something about Cochiti (cf. Batkin 1999).\r\n\r\nThe figure is a single, seated man, holding drum that is loosely placed in his hands. Cochiti is well known for its drum making and ceramic traditions. The figure therefore reminds us of positive cultural attributes of the village. The man is dressed in ceremonial clothing and his uplifted head, open eyes and mouth tells us he is singing. Newly composed songs are used during Cochiti dances, evoking fertility for the village, its crops and people. These ceremonies most often consist of dancers and a men’s chorus, some of whom beat drums to set the rhythm of the dance and song, as well as emulate the life-giving sounds of thunder. He wears a feathered headdress, which at first might strike the viewer as an Indian stereotype of feathers and bonnets. But the meaning here may indeed be more nuanced because there are particular Cochiti dances in which dancers and/or the chorus wear bonnets to honor their relations with southern Plains groups such as the Comanche. In a complex meddling of cultures we find the continuation of early single figurine intentionality in this figurine.\r\n\r\nLooking more closely, the figure is as much document as whimsical. When this piece was made Cochiti’s pottery tradition had slowed in response to the availability of manufactured metal ware and crockery. As wells and plumbing brought water closer or into individual homes, older style water jars were not as essential. Changing economic patterns of working in or outside of the home for wages reduced some reliance on agriculture. On the other hand, supplementing one’s crops and husbandry became increasingly important as store-bought necessities like coffee, sugar, flour, and cloth were integrated into the village life. Cash was needed to purchase these goods; and there is little doubt that Romero made this figure to sell to non-Indians to earn money. When Elisabeth Houtzager visited in 1965, she bought the piece and had the potter sign it by pencil. \r\n\r\nBruce Bernstein; Coe Foundation for the Arts\r\nSanta Fe, NM; 2015\r\n\r\nBarbara Babcock et.al., The Pueblo Storyteller: Development of a Figurative Ceramic Tradition; University of Arizona Press; Tucson, 1986. Jonathan Batkin, Clay People: Pueblo Indian Figurative Traditions; Wheelwright Museum; Santa Fe, 1999.\r\n \r\nTraditioneel Cochiti aardewerk heeft een gebroken-witte slip en werd in zwart en rood beschilderd. Opvallend is de productie van aardewerk figuurtjes, zowel van dieren als mensen. Deze productie kreeg vooral een impuls doordat handelaren in Santa Fe deze goed aan toeristen wisten te verkopen nadat in 1883 de stad een verbinding kreeg met de transcontinentale spoorweg. Door de massaproductie ging de kwaliteit snel achteruit en vanwege de ruwe vorm werden deze figuurtjes \"monos\" genoemd, het Spaanse woord voor aapjes. Tussen 1910 en 1930 begonnen enkele vrouwen zich echter weer toe te leggen op kwalitatief goed aardewerk.\r\n\r\nPottenbakster Laurencita Herrera (1912-1984) en haar man Nestor Herrera, belnd om zijn trommels, stonden aan het hoofd van een grote pottenbakkersfamilie. Haar dochter Seferina Ortiz (geb. 1931) ontwikkelde de kunst van miniatuurfiguren verder en leerde dit aan haar drie dochters en zoon Virgil (geb. 1969). Deze laatste vervolmaakte het ambacht en kunstenaarschap in klei door de productie van bijna levensgrote figuren van velerlei aard, waaronder circusmensen, carnavalstypes en mensen in leren s/m-kleding.\r\n\r\nHelen Cordero (geb. 19  ) introduceerde een nieuwe figuur die een onnavolgbaar succes beleefde: een zittende vrouwenfiguur met kleine kinderen op haar schoot, benen, armen, rug en schouders die hen een verhaal vertelt en toepasselijk \"storyteller\" wordt genoemd. Inmiddels wordt deze figuur in vele pueblos gemaakt en treft men variaties aan, o.a. met beren.\r\n(Pieter Hovens, 2000)" .
